# UDS Site Changelog

Whenever you modify a file inside `uds-docs/`, append a `SITE_CHANGELOG`
entry to `uds-docs/data/site-changelog.ts`. That's the whole contract
post-migration.

The SITE-versioning apparatus (`version.txt`, `bump-site.sh`, the
`?v=N` cache-bust query params, the auto-reload polling) was removed
during Chunk 17 of the Next.js migration. Cache-busting is now
Cloudflare's job (per `_headers`); cache invalidation on deploy is
Next's job (content-hashed asset URLs).

## How to add an entry

1. Open `uds-docs/data/site-changelog.ts`.
2. Append a new object to the `SITE_CHANGELOG` array — newest entries
   go LAST in the array; the renderer reverses for display:

```ts
{
  version: '2026.06.04.1',
  date: '2026-06-04',
  changes: [
    { type: 'added', text: 'Wired the version dropdown to the active UDS context.' },
  ],
},
```

- `version` is a free-form bump string. Pick `YYYY.MM.DD.N` where `N`
  resets to 1 each day. The version is informational only — it's not
  read by any audit, fetcher, or cache layer.
- `date` is the actual calendar date. Use ISO 8601 (`YYYY-MM-DD`).
  Never guess; use `date -u +%Y-%m-%d` if you need to look it up.
- `type` is one of `added`, `changed`, `fixed`, `removed`.
- If multiple changes ship in one session, batch them into a single
  entry with multiple `changes` items.

## Voice and length

SITE_CHANGELOG entries appear on the live Changelog page. They are read
by humans, not by audits. Write them the way the early entries did —
short, descriptive, designer-readable.

### Audience

The reader is a senior product designer. Technically literate — they
understand tokens, components, file structure, the difference between a
CSS class and a React component. They are not asking to be talked down
to. They are also not reading the changelog to debug code; they are
reading it to know what shipped.

### Test for whether to use a technical term

Use the term when the reader will need the exact name to act on it —
copy a token, find a file, debug a regression, search the codebase.
Skip it when it is decoration. If the same idea fits in plain language
without losing accuracy or making the sentence longer, use plain
language. Same test [`communication-style.mdc`](./communication-style.mdc)
uses for chat replies; it applies to written entries too.

### Length and shape

- **Most entries are 1–3 sentences.** Substantial changes (component
  rewritten, page redesigned, multi-system restructure) can run a few
  more, but if you are past one short paragraph you are narrating
  implementation, not the change.
- **Lead with what changed**, not the steps you took to change it.
- **File paths and function names are fine when they orient** — not
  required, not the point.
- **No line numbers** (`lines 102-107`). Files change; line numbers go
  stale immediately.
- **No internal phase terminology** (`Phase 13 restructure`,
  `RUN_ID nav-header-...`, "the proof-of-fix for X workflow"). The
  reader does not have that context.
- **No merge-resolution narratives.** "Merged with main; both branches
  bumped to .5; resolved to .6." is a commit-message detail, not a
  changelog entry.
- **Exact tag names go in backticks** (`` `<select>` ``). The renderer
  escapes literal `<` / `>` in entry text so they show as text — but
  backticks render as `<code>` and read better.

If the change is genuinely big, write a one-line summary as the entry
and put the implementation detail in the per-component
`changelog.json`, the PR description, or the commit message. Those
artifacts have technical voice non-negotiable per
[`communication-style.mdc`](./communication-style.mdc) §"Where
technical voice is non-negotiable".

## Exceptions

- Don't create a site changelog entry for changes that only affect
  files outside `uds-docs/` (e.g. editing Cursor rules, audits, the
  repo-root `scripts/` directory).
- Don't create an entry for changes to per-component `uds/components/`
  files — those have their own `changelog.json` per component, and
  `uds/CHANGELOG.json` aggregates them. The SITE changelog is for the
  docs-site itself.
